1. Introduction
Sustainable solvent selection is a key challenge in modern chemical processes, particularly in reducing environmental impact and improving safety. This project applies a data-driven approach to evaluate the sustainability of commonly used organic solvents using molecular descriptors. The aim is to demonstrate how computational analysis can support green chemistry principles in industrial applications.
________________________________________
2. Objective
To evaluate and compare the sustainability of chemical solvents by analyzing molecular properties and deriving key environmental and chemical indicators.
________________________________________
3. Methodology
Data for selected solvents were obtained through API access from PubChem. The analysis is based on proxy indicators derived from molecular descriptors and is intended for preliminary screening rather than regulatory assessment. The following molecular descriptors were analyzed:
•	Molecular weight 
•	XLogP (hydrophobicity indicator) 
From these descriptors, additional chemical and environmental properties were derived:
•	Polarity (inverse relation to XLogP) 
•	Solubility (based on polarity trends) 
•	Environmental persistence (correlated with hydrophobicity) 
•	Toxicity implications (approximated through logP values) 
A comparative case study was conducted between benzene (a traditional solvent) and ethanol (a greener alternative).

